			      <div type="translation" xml:lang="eng">
				        <ab>In the ... year of King Siri-Ehavalacāntamūla ... fortnight of winter, ... day. The memorial pillar of Koṇḍa..., treasurer of the noble ones (?), borne on the shoulders by...</ab>
			      </div>
			      <div type="commentary">
				        <listApp>
					          <app loc="2">
						            <note>Sircar assumes <foreign xml:lang="san-Latn">bhaṭṭāraka</foreign>, but an association with
								<foreign xml:lang="san-Latn">bhaṇḍāra</foreign>
							and cognate forms with the meaning “treasurer,
							officer in charge of the treasury” seems more
							probable due to the clearly visible anusvāra above
							the akṣara <seg type="graphemic">bha</seg>.</note>
					          </app>
					          <app loc="3">
						            <note>For <foreign xml:lang="pra-Latn">kha<unclear>ṁ</unclear>dhikata</foreign>
							(Sanskrit <foreign xml:lang="san-Latn">skandhīkr̥ta</foreign>), “borne on the
							shoulder”, see <bibl>
								                <ptr target="eiad-bibl:Sircara"/>: <citedRange>13</citedRange>
							              </bibl>. We are unable to confirm the reading of the
							preceding akṣaras suggested by Sircar (<foreign xml:lang="pra-Latn">yati-samaṇa</foreign>).
						</note>
					          </app>
				        </listApp>
			      </div>
